At Stake in this Election:

All 50 seats in the Solomon Islands National Parliament

Provincial assembly and Honiara city council elections will take place concurrently.
Government Structure: 

Chief of State: King CHARLES III (since 8 September 2022)

Represented by Governor General David VUNAGI (since 8 July 2019)


Head of Government: Prime Minister Manasseh SOGAVARE (since 24 April 2019)
Assembly: unicameral National Parliament with 50 seats

Electoral System: 

The King is a hereditary monarch.
The Governor General is nominated by the National Parliament and appointed by the monarch. The Governor General may serve up to two 5-year terms.
The Prime Minister, typically the parliamentary majority leader, is elected by the National Parliament following each general election.
In the National Parliament, all 50 members are directly elected by plurality vote from single-seat constituencies. All members serve 4-year terms.

Last Election:
In the 2019 parliamentary election, independent candidates won the largest share of seats (21). Eight coalitions and parties also won seats. Voter turnout was 67.54%.
Information for Voters:
Voter and Civic Awareness Materials (in English)
New/Unique in this Election: 
The postponement of the general election was enacted in September 2022 with the passage of the Constitution (Amendment) Bill 2022. The postponement delayed the next general election from 2023 to 2024. The government's official reason was to avoid having the election conflict with the 2023 Pacific Games, which the Solomon Islands hosted. 
Key Deadlines:

Candidate filing deadline: 6 March 2024
Voter registration deadline: 11 September 2024
